This got deleted, which I think is fine.
nit: you can return here, then you don't need the "else" branch
Seems reasonable but would like those error traces that got deleted
Maybe use template function type to be consistent with bmcweb code?

> Maybe use template function type to be consistent with bmcweb code?

There is no stronger requirement to use template or std::function here, I tend to use std::function because its callback parameters are well known.

> Why not just use MapperGetSubTreePathsResponse ?

No, That's not the right way, although they describe the same attributes, but their meanings are completely different, that's a lazy way 😊
Can we do the `ec` check inside the `callback` to align with the surrounding codes?
nit: suggest to move the line lambda function into a separate function.

> nit: suggest to move the line lambda function into a separate function.

Ed suggest
```
Either leave it the way it is as an rvalue, or move it over to the new pattern of a normal method.
```
I choose to keep rvalue
Is it possible to just return and don't set the internal error if the `dbus::utility::MapperEndPoints` container is empty?

> Is it possible to just return and don't set the internal error if the `dbus::utility::MapperEndPoints` container is empty?

Sorry, This commit just refactors the getAssociaitonEndPoints method without paying attention to its function, and I will not change the logic of the original author to implement it.
Why can't we just pass callback directly?  This lambda looks like it does nothing.

> Why can't we just pass callback directly?  This lambda looks like it does nothing.

Thanks Ed, Ack.

For next time, an explanation from https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/architecture/object-mapper.md#associations about how this works would help. :) 

When an object with, for example, an object path of pathA uses the following values:

["foo", "bar", "pathB"]

The mapper will create 2 new objects:

    pathA/foo
    pathB/bar
Should be string_view for new code?  As written, this is going to point to an rvalue, so (I think?) it's undefined behavior.

> Should be string_view for new code?  As written, this is going to point to an rvalue, so (I think?) it's undefined behavior.

At present, only `const std::string&` is accepted in sdbusplus, but not `std::string_view`
https://github.com/openbmc/sdbusplus/blob/master/include/sdbusplus/asio/property.hpp#L45
https://github.com/openbmc/sdbusplus/blob/master/include/sdbusplus/asio/connection.hpp#L202

Can we just intergrate this into the utility function itself?  Otherwise, this "create a dbus path" will be duplicated in every caller of the utility function, and I can't think of any reason why you wouldn't use the typesafe path.

Could be done in a different path if you wanted.

> Can we just intergrate this into the utility function itself?  Otherwise, this "create a dbus path" will be duplicated in every caller of the utility function, and I can't think of any reason why you wouldn't use the typesafe path.
> 
> Could be done in a different path if you wanted.

Ack.
And I will completely refactor everything using the `endpoints` method in the next commit
Wouldn't it be restated like - "Since they are general methods,"?
This has sat a while. It seems reasonable to me to move forward with this.
